","Normandie, France":"Normandie, Frankrijk","Somme, Cher, Centre-Val de Loire, France":"Somme, Cher, Centre, Frankrijk","Crécy, , Picardie, France":"Crécy, Oise, Picardie, Frankrijk","France":"Frankrijk","Rouen, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, France":"Rouen, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, Frankrijk"},"en":{"1450–1515":"1450–1515","1450–1510":"1450–1510","1470–1532":"1470–1532","1475–1565":"1475–1565","1477–Male":"1477–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","Abt 1470":"about 1470","1477":"1477","1565":"1565","1532":"1532","1510":"1510","1475":"1475","1450":"1450","about 1475":"about 1475","1470":"1470","Abt 1477":"about 1477","24 October 1510":"24 October 1510","1515":"1515","Crécy-en-Ponthieu, Somme, Picardie, France":"Crécy-en-Ponthieu, Somme, Picardie, France","Normandie, France":"Normandy, France","Somme, Cher, Centre-Val de Loire, France":"Somme, Cher, Centre, France","Crécy, , Picardie, France":"Crécy, Oise, Picardie, France","France":"France","Rouen, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, France":"Rouen, Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Delange","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Dutch Andries, Cor, Dirk, Geert, Gerrit, Willem.","Dutch and Flemish: nickname meaning ‘the tall (one)’, a variant of   Lange   with the definite article <i>de</i> ‘the’. The surname <i>De Lange</i> is also established in South Africa. Compare   Delong   2.","French (<b>Delange</b>): patronymic, with fused preposition <i>de</i> ‘of’, from the nickname <i>L'Ange</i> ‘the angel’, or a topographic or habitational name referring to a house or inn distinguished by the sign of an angel."],"variants":[{"name":"Delong","meanings":["French: habitational name, with fused preposition <i>de</i> ‘from’, denoting someone from a place called Long, of which there are examples in Cher, Dordogne, and Somme.","Americanized form of Dutch and Flemish   De Lange   1 and of its Flemish cognate <b>De Langhe</b>, which is also found in France (Nord and Pas-de-Calais)."]},{"name":"Lange","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Hans, Erwin, Heinz, Horst, Otto, Wolfgang, Ernst, Helmut, Hermann, Manfred, Reinhold.","German, Scandinavian, and Dutch: variant of   Lang   ‘long’. This surname is also found in Poland and in France (Alsace and Lorraine). Compare   De Lange  .","French: variant, with fused definite article <i>l'</i>, of   Ange   2. Compare   Longe   1."]}]},{"name":"Jeanne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Feminine form of   Jean ."],"variants":[{"name":"Jane","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Jeanne Delange was born in 1450, in Rouen, Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France as the daughter of Inconnu. She married Alexandre Gaillard about 1470, in Crécy, Oise, Picardie, France. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died in 1515, in Somme, Cher, Centre, France, at the age of 65, and was buried in Somme, Cher, Centre, France."},"et":{"1450–1515":"1450–1515","1450–1510":"1450–1510","1470–1532":"1470–1532","1475–1565":"1475–1565","1477–Male":"1477–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","Abt 1470":"umbes 1470","1477":"1477","1565":"1565","1532":"1532","1510":"1510","1475":"1475","1450":"1450","about 1475":"umbes 1475","1470":"1470","Abt 1477":"umbes 1477","24 October 1510":"24. oktoober 1510","1515":"1515","Crécy-en-Ponthieu, Somme, Picardie, France":"Crécy-en-Ponthieu, Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","Normandie, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Somme, Cher, Centre-Val de Loire, France":"Somme, Cher, Centre, Prantsusmaa","Crécy, , Picardie, France":"Crécy, Oise, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa","Rouen, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, France":"Rouen, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1450–1515":"1450–1515","1450–1510":"1450–1510","1470–1532":"1470–1532","1475–1565":"1475–1565","1477–Male":"1477–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","Abt 1470":"noin 1470","1477":"1477","1565":"1565","1532":"1532","1510":"1510","1475":"1475","1450":"1450","about 1475":"noin 1475","1470":"1470","Abt 1477":"noin 1477","24 October 1510":"24. lokakuuta 1510","1515":"1515","Crécy-en-Ponthieu, Somme, Picardie, France":"Crécy-en-Ponthieu, Somme, Picardie, Ranska","Normandie, France":"Normandie, Ranska","Somme, Cher, Centre-Val de Loire, France":"Somme, Cher, Centre, Ranska","Crécy, , Picardie, France":"Crécy, Oise, Picardie, Ranska","France":"Ranska","Rouen, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, France":"Rouen, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, Ranska"},"fr":{"1450–1515":"1450–1515",